  <a href="#1" id="1">
   New treatments
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   that stop a heart attack in its tracks,
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   may help victims leave the hospital as early as three days after their attacks.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   Early discharges were made possible by two medical advances, tissue plasminogen activator
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   (TPA)
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   and angioplasty.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   TPA can dissolve clots in the heart's arteries
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   and minimize damage and angioplasty can clear arteries
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   by opening them with tiny balloons.
  </a>
  <a href="#10" id="10">
   Hospital stays have been steadily shortening over the past decades as doctors learned
  </a>
  <a href="#11" id="11">
   that prolonged inactivity caused patients to develop blood clots
  </a>
  <a href="#12" id="12">
   and become demoralized. If 15% of heart attack patients were discharges after three days,
  </a>
  <a href="#13" id="13">
   the annual savings would be $280 million.
  </a>
